05836nam a22010815i 9780691213231DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20202009nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912132317 a10.1515/97806912132312doi  a(DE-B1597)554865  a(OCoLC)1158145967  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aBUS0670002bisacsh04a330.974712221 aCurrid-Halkett, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Warhol Economy :bHow Fashion, Art, and Music Drive New York City - New Edition /cElizabeth Currid-Halkett. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b20 halftones. 22 line illus. 5 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the Paperback Edition: Uncreative Destruction -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. ART, CULTURE, AND NEW YORK CITY -- tChapter 2. HOW IT ALL BEGAN: From the Rise of the Factory to the Rise of Bling -- tChapter 3. BECOMING CREATIVE -- tChapter 4. THE SOCIAL LIFE OF CREATIVITY -- tChapter 5. THE ECONOMICS OF A DANCE FLOOR -- tChapter 6. CREATING BUZZ, SELLING COOL -- tChapter 7, THE RISE OF GLOBAL TASTEMAKERS: What It All Means for the Policymakers -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhich is more important to New York City's economy, the gleaming corporate office--or the grungy rock club that launches the best new bands? If you said "office," think again. In The Warhol Economy, Elizabeth Currid argues that creative industries like fashion, art, and music drive the economy of New York as much as--if not more than--finance, real estate, and law. And these creative industries are fueled by the social life that whirls around the clubs, galleries, music venues, and fashion shows where creative people meet, network, exchange ideas, pass judgments, and set the trends that shape popular culture. The implications of Currid's argument are far-reaching, and not just for New York. Urban policymakers, she suggests, have not only seriously underestimated the importance of the cultural economy, but they have failed to recognize that it depends on a vibrant creative social scene. They haven't understood, in other words, the social, cultural, and economic mix that Currid calls the Warhol economy. With vivid first-person reporting about New York's creative scene, Currid takes the reader into the city spaces where the social and economic lives of creativity merge. The book has fascinating original interviews with many of New York's important creative figures, including fashion designers Zac Posen and Diane von Furstenberg, artists Ryan McGinness and Futura, and members of the band Clap Your Hands Say Yeah. The economics of art and culture in New York and other cities has been greatly misunderstood and underrated. The Warhol Economy explains how the cultural economy works-and why it is vital to all great cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCultural industrieszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aPopular culturexEconomic aspectszNew York (State)zNew York. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Urban & Regional.2bisacsh  aAdidas.  aBecker, Howard.  aBell, Daniel.  aBloomberg, Michael.  aBungalow.  aCameron, Martina.  aCastells, Manuel.  aClark, Terry.  aCosta, Francisco.  aDeitch Projects.  aDeitch, Jeffrey.  aFashion Week.  aFutura 2000.  aGlaeser, Edward.  aGuertin, Robbie.  aHaring, Keith.  aHernandez, Lazaro.  aJacobs, Jane.  aJones, Quincy.  aKlein, Calvin.  aManhattan.  aMcGinness, Ryan.  aNew York Post.  aPiore, Michael.  aRalph Lauren.  aSan Francisco.  aeducation.  afilmmakers.